"Vitrectomy: Definition, Details & Recovery800.223.2273100 Years of Cleveland ClinicMyChartNeed Help?GivingCareersSearchClevelandClinic.orgFind A DoctorLocations & DirectionsPatients & VisitorsHealth LibraryInstitutes & DepartmentsAppointmentsHome/Health Library/Treatments & Procedures/VitrectomyAdvertisementAdvertisementAdvertisementVitrectomyA vitrectomy is an eye surgery that removes the vitreous fluid from your eyeball. It can be done to remove cloudy fluid or fluid with debris or to do repairs on your retina or macula. The vitreous is replaced with a clear fluid or a gas bubble until your body begins producing the vitreous again.ContentsArrow DownOverviewProcedure DetailsRisks / BenefitsRecovery and OutlookWhen to Call the DoctorContentsArrow DownOverviewProcedure DetailsRisks / BenefitsRecovery and OutlookWhen to Call the DoctorOverviewA surgeon will perform a vitrectomy to treat conditions related to the vitreous humor or the retina of your eye.What is a vitrectomy?A vitrectomy is a surgery to remove the vitreous humor (the vitreous) of your eye. The vitreous humor is a gel-like substance that fills the center of your eyeball.During a vitrectomy, your surgeon removes the vitreous. They may then do repairs on your retina, which is at the back of your eye. Your retina is the part of your eye that converts light into electrical signals that it sends to your brain.Your surgeon may replace the vitreous humor with sterile salt water, silicone oil or a gas bubble. This step helps your eye keep its shape and your retina stay in position.What does a vitrectomy treat?You may need a vitrectomy if you have an eye condition that:Causes your vitreous to become cloudy. This is often due to vitreous hemorrhage or bleeding in your eye.Causes pulling on or damage to your retina.Isn\u2019t easy to diagnose.Needs a drug delivery or therapeutic device.What retinal and macular conditions do surgeons treat with vitrectomy?Retinal detachment: Your retina pulls away from its supporting tissue.Posterior vitreous detachment: Your vitreous gel pulls away from your retina.Diabetes-related retinopathy: The blood vessels in your retina leak and grow abnormally.Macular hole: You have a hole in the center of your macula, which is the center of your retina.Macular pucker: Your macula develops a wrinkle or a crease.Retinopathy of prematurity: Scar tissue forms from blood vessel growth in the eyes of premature babies.What non-retinal conditions do surgeons treat with vitrectomy?Eye injury: Damage to your eye, including from scratches or punctures.Endophthalmitis: An infection inside your eye.Tumors: Vitrectomy can be a way to biopsy a tumor in your eye.Lens issues: Providers sometimes use vitrectomy to address cataracts and dislocated lenses.Drug delivery: Your healthcare provider can use a vitrectomy to place drug delivery devices. These drugs may be steroids, gene therapy and antiviral drugs.What are the types of vitrectomy?The type of vitrectomy you have will depend on the diseased part of your eye.Anterior vitrectomyYou may need an anterior vitrectomy if you have vitreous leakage in the front part of your eye. The anterior chamber (the front part of your eye) contains your iris and lens. An ophthalmologist can perform an anterior vitrectomy. You may need a retina specialist to do a pars plana vitrectomy on the posterior chamber of your eye.Posterior pars plana vitrectomyA posterior pars plana vitrectomy treats conditions that affect the back (posterior) part of your eye. The pars plana is the flat part of the ciliary body of your eye. The posterior contains your retina, retinal pigment epithelium, choroid and sclera. It also contains the vitreous cavity, which holds the vitreous.How common is vitrectomy surgery?In the United States, surgeons do about 225,000 vitrectomies each year. The number is likely to continue to grow as eye care providers find more uses for vitrectomy.AdvertisementCleveland Clinic is a non-profit academic medical center. Advertis